From cccbe8b9cd2d05be9b41e77fa074d751627f847e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: dfattal <dfattal@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 14:56:17 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 40/40] inline-3d(#625): delay-load openxr_loader.dll so the
 sandboxed renderer survives
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

A patched non-component build never showed a browser window (displayxr-browser#15).
The cause is one line of link config, and nothing of ours had to run: with zero
flags set, chrome.dll's import table alone did it.

third_party/displayxr's openxr_loader_link config linked the loader's import lib
plainly. In a component build that import lands in the weave_client DLL, which
only the browser and GPU processes ever load. In a non-component build every
component collapses into chrome.dll, so chrome.dll itself imports
openxr_loader.dll — and every process must then resolve it at load time. The
renderer is sandboxed (low integrity, restricted token) and cannot load a DLL
outside its policy, so it died before running any Blink code.

Measured against vanilla upstream on the same machine, same staging, same ACLs:
identical browser/gpu/utility/crashpad counts, and 3 renderers vs our 0.
--no-sandbox brought 4 renderers back, which isolates the sandbox from a crash.

Zero renderers is what produced the reported symptom. The toolbar WebUI's JS
never ran, so it never reached app.ts:335 onPageInitialized(), so
InitialWebUIManager::OnWebUIToolbarLoaded() never fired, so the RequestDeferShow
gate at the top of BrowserView::Show() never released and the window stayed
hidden forever. The frame pumping messages and Viz never drawing were both
downstream of the same emptiness.

Delay-loading resolves on the first xr* call instead. Renderers never make one.
The two processes that do are both safe: the browser is unsandboxed, and the GPU
process creates its weave session pre-sandbox in gpu_main.cc, which is exactly
when the delay-load fires.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 third_party/displayxr/BUILD.gn | 18 ++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 18 insertions(+)

diff --git a/third_party/displayxr/BUILD.gn b/third_party/displayxr/BUILD.gn
index 3ecafc90fb7c5..b647c9ab8ab94 100644
--- a/third_party/displayxr/BUILD.gn
+++ b/third_party/displayxr/BUILD.gn
@@ -16,9 +16,27 @@ config("openxr_headers") {
 
 # Link the prebuilt OpenXR loader import lib (CRT-neutral). lib_dirs is resolved
 # relative to this BUILD.gn directory.
+#
+# DELAYLOAD is load-bearing, not an optimization (displayxr-browser#15). A plain
+# import puts openxr_loader.dll in the import table of whatever links this. In a
+# component build that is only the weave_client DLL, which just the browser and
+# GPU processes ever load. In a NON-component build every component collapses
+# into chrome.dll, so chrome.dll itself imports the loader — and then EVERY
+# process resolves it at load time, including the renderer, which is sandboxed
+# (low integrity, restricted token) and cannot load a DLL outside its policy. It
+# dies before running any Blink code, leaving zero renderers and, downstream, a
+# browser window that never shows.
+#
+# Delay-loading resolves on the first xr* call instead. Renderers never make one.
+# The two processes that do are both safe: the browser is unsandboxed, and the
+# GPU process creates its weave session pre-sandbox in gpu_main.cc (#625), which
+# is exactly when the delay-load fires.
 config("openxr_loader_link") {
   libs = [ "openxr_loader.lib" ]
   lib_dirs = [ "lib" ]
+  if (is_win) {
+    ldflags = [ "/DELAYLOAD:openxr_loader.dll" ]
+  }
 }
 
 # Depend on this to compile against + link the OpenXR loader.
